04776nam a22007215i 9780813565323DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142015nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2014930070  a97808135653237 a10.36019/97808135653232doi  a(DE-B1597)526507  a(OCoLC)960195820  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aQB791.3b.K44 2014 4aQB791.3b.K44 2014 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a523.11262231 aKeeton, Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Ray of Light in a Sea of Dark Matter /cCharles Keeton. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2014] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (104 p.) :b15 b-w images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPinpoints00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. What’s in the Dark? -- t2. When Mass Is Like Glass -- t3. How Do You Weigh a Galaxy? -- t4. Is Dark Matter MACHO or WIMPy? -- t5. Finding What’s Missing -- t6. “A Long Time Ago in a Galaxy Far, Far Away” -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tNotes on Sources -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat’s in the dark? Countless generations have gazed up at the night sky and asked this question—the same question that cosmologists ask themselves as they study the universe. The answer turns out to be surprising and rich. The space between stars is filled with an exotic substance called “dark matter” that exerts gravity but does not emit, absorb, or reflect light. The space between galaxies is rife with “dark energy” that creates a sort of cosmic antigravity causing the expansion of the universe to accelerate. Together, dark matter and dark energy account for 95 percent of the content of the universe. News reporters and science journalists routinely talk about these findings using terms that they assume we have a working knowledge of, but do you really understand how astronomers arrive at their findings or what it all means? Cosmologists face a conundrum: how can we study substances we cannot see, let alone manipulate? A powerful approach is to observe objects whose motion is influenced by gravity. Einstein predicted that gravity can act like a lens to bend light. Today we see hundreds of cases of this—instances where the gravity of a distant galaxy distorts our view of a more distant object, creating multiple images or spectacular arcs on the sky. Gravitational lensing is now a key part of the international quest to understand the invisible substance that surrounds us, penetrates us, and binds the universe together. A Ray of Light in a Sea of Dark Matter offers readers a concise, accessible explanation of how astronomers probe dark matter. Readers quickly gain an understanding of what might be out there, how scientists arrive at their findings, and why this research is important to us. Engaging and insightful, Charles Keeton gives everyone an opportunity to be an active learner and listener in our ever-expanding universe. Watch a video with Charles Keeton: Watch video now. (http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Uc3byXNS1G0).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDark matter (Astronomy) 0aDark matter (Astronomy). 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066615140uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081356532340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813565323423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813565323.jpg  a978-3-11-066615-1  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  a